occurrenceRemarks: Large tree to 25m, DBH 70cm, one single trunk first branching at 15m, crown in form of an inverted cone. Bark smooth, patched white and shades of grey. Wood very hard, slash whitish. Foliage deep green, leathery, petiole and leaf rachis yellowish. Habitat being totally destroyed - trees being cut for charcoal and fence posts (including C. ferrea). Area eventually grassed for cattle. As in coastal areas, Chloroleucon tortum also present, with very similar bark but softer timber and contorted sinuey trunk. Same species as Lewis 1623 but coastal specimen, multiple-trunked, of lower stature and different crown shape. Wood sample takem from cut timber on ground (almost certainly from a different tree in the area) - produces a ringing sound when chopped, very hard and difficult to saw. Spirit & wood sample, photographs. Sterile.
